.....    Humpty was pushed</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=taranna>Taranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>HiElf Snob</span><br>  Posts: 606<br> <font color=#333333>(3/18/03 11:00:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub83.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1939.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: France offers compermise?</span><hr size=1> Responding in order:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Only their interest is Money, while ours are Safety. They have billions in contracts with Iraq for oil and in many other areas of trade.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I find that statement ludicrous and presumptious Alt.  You don't suppose that the fact that 87% of the French people are against military action is the real reason for the French government position for example?  Governments are mandates of the people- with such a clear majority against the war, the French administration have done their democratic duty.  When opinion is split (55% of Americans polled yesterday support war, 37% are against it without UN backing- 74% of people polled are anxious about the war result)- when opinion is that split, it behoves the US administration to make the correct strategic decision to protect its people in the long run- it hasn't done it.  <br>
<br>
As regards your claims of &quot;French oil deals&quot;- the facts are as follows:  A small number of French companies (5 I believe, including eLF)- have pre-contract agreements to start negotiations <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>in the event sanctions are lifted</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Let's think about that for a moment.  You are saying that the French <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>government</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> has based its entire foreign policy position regarding Iraq on the whim of a few French corporations?  Why in heaven's name Altaris, would the French adopt such a risky and potentially damaging stance, risking US/UK economic boycotts for the sake of a few pre-contractual agreements for a few French companies who mainly sell their oil overseas?  That's right folks!  France is a rather interesting nation energy-wise, less than an eigth of their national energy needs come from oil- and most of that is imported car petroleum from <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>British Petroleum</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, a UK firm whose European export market naturally derives from <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>North Sea oil</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->- <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>not</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Middle Eastern oil.  Nationally speaking France have comitted to nuclear power for energy generation since the late 1970s- not many people know that in America, so the &quot;French oil deals&quot; are an easy sell to the population there.  <br>
<br>
And let us assume for a moment Alt, that you are right, and that &quot;Money&quot; is the driving agenda here, and that it is indeed 5 oil corporations that dictate the foreign policy of France.  Why then, haven't the French <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>ever</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> veto'd sanctions?  I put it to you that this would give them exactly what they want, and be a far less risky veto than even the threatened one they put to the draft resolution recently.  It wouldn't have lead the French to a position of brinkmanship facing the United States, it would certainly not have had the effect of such diplomatic dynamite.  That veto would clearly give them all the room they needed to trade with Iraq openly and at far less political risk than they now have faced.  The simple truth is that the French have supported a position of inspections, backed with containment, disarmament and the ever present <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>threat</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of force- their position is a legitimate one that supports international law and institutions- it is also the correct strategic choice.<br>
<br>
Just as a point of law by the way Altaris- the fall of the Ba'ath party in no way makes these agreements void- the agreement is between French corporations and Iraqi corporations.  Assuming any invading army doesn't seek to restructure every major business that has a contract with foreign MNCs, it's fair to say that the agreements still have a legal basis.  Moreover, there is strong legal precedent in the Common Law(Iraq uses a common law system like the UK) for binding agreement to take effect even in the event of an illegal contract- Sale of Goods Act (1965).  There are also similar precedents under Napoleonic law provisions in France- <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Guillaume contre Everschard </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->(1912).  Therefore- even in the absence of a binding contract: pre-contractual agreements to negotiate terms are still valid even before the actual sale of goods- in the interests of protecting the party pursuing agreement.  Legal nomenclature aside- in layman's terms it basically means that in the absence of a complete liquidation of Iraqi business by an invading army, the obligations of agreement would be valid, even if an Iraqi court one day pronounced them illegal.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I need to find the transcript of the speech I saw Blair giving before I came to work, it was a really good one. To bad Blair can't be our Pres. While I fully support Bush, I have always loved Blair.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I watched the PM's speech, and indeed the rest of the debate in the Commons, including the resignation statements of 3 deputy cabinet ministers- particularly the Deputy Home Secretary.  I do not doubt that our Prime Minister believes passionately in the correctness of his action- indeed, as the DHS pointed out- if passion and courage of conviction were the motion on the floor of the Commons, the Prime Minister would win every vote in the House.  But he went on to note, as did many other key (former) government ministers who had resigned, that courage of conviction and belief were not enough in themselves to commit British troops to war.  <br>
<br>
That is the issue at hand Altaris- suspicion, prevarication, unproven linkages, assertions and aggressive rhetoric cannot be allowed to bludgeon the facts and the proven doctrines of containment and deterrence.  As much as I admired the PM's speech, he said nothing that he hasn't already- and even conceded that Saddam's terrorist links were &quot;loose at best&quot; and then made an (unproven) assertion that &quot;they are hardening&quot;.  That is a poorly defined threat- in my mind the case for a pre-emptive mode of action requires a far higher standard of proof than any regular military response- and we haven't seen a shred of proof indicating such a threat.  We must act on information in hand- and in the absence of information presenting a threat we should not act.  I find it just as contradictory as Robin Cook did- that we should claim the Iraqi military structure weak enough to collapse at the mere sight of Coalition forces- and yet still somehow claim that Iraq poses a clear threat to us...is ludicrous.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>No, diplomacy was NOT over when troops were deployed. Troops can be called back<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Heh, in theory- yet I ask you to consider this lurker- why were 60,000 US troops and 28,000 British troops already being deployed to the region long before Resolution 1441 was even tabled?  And why were those 28,000 British troops packing enough supplies for a force nearly twice its size at the time?  The seeds of regime change were laid long before disarmament ever hit the UNSC debating tables.  This indicates most strongly that disarmament was likely sought as a pretext for a UN rubber stamp for military action rather than the vehicle for decision-making.  <br>
<br>
You talk of troops being recalled- yet there has <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>never</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> been a climb-down of deployment when so many troops have been deployed- it has <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>never</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> happened historically- and so it has proved again.  Once those troops are deployed, it is humiliating, not to mention political suicide to even consider backing down- whether or not standing down is the right thing to do.  <br>
<br>
Why do you think the United States were committed as long as they were in Vietnam lurker- or why did the British press ahead with Suez in 1956?  It wasn't just because of the lack of an exit strategy- it was because it would have been a humilitating defeat for the United States(or the UK in the latter case) in terms of failing to defeat communism in SE Asia/Arab nationalism respectively- failure was not an option for the politicans, and millions of people paid the price.  Pulling out would have signalled the end for any administration countenancing it except in the face of overwhelming losses- I'm saddened that it took that level of bloodshed to &quot;realize&quot; that the action itself was wrong.  Politicians only give the order to withdraw if in doing so, their own political survival is assured- they will only climb down when it is politically viable to do so.  If that precious survival of theirs is threatened in any way- then even unjust wars will be engaged in and conflicts escalated to keep them firmly in their offices.  Sad, but true.<br>
<br>
Now, to Bollix's comments.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>i will give a few select quotes from Robin Cooke, a highly respected, and high up government member (he is/was Leader of the House of Commons) in the UK who resigned in protest at this war.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I cannot praise Robin Cook highly enough for his speech and action in resigning from an administration which he disagreed with in principle.  Robin Cook, for those who don't know- was the former Foreign Secretary in the last Parliament, recently Leader of the Commons and before that was a senior figure in the Shadow Cabinet for 30 odd years.  A consumate politician who spent his life at the heart of the Labour party felt the need to walk away from everything he held dear- to abaondon Tony Blair, whose election campaign he managed, to abandon some of his closest personal friends in the political sense.  I cannot imagine what courage it must have taken for the third most powerful administrative figure in the country, a talisman of the Central Labour party, to resign his position when he had everything to gain by blindly supporting the government- my hat's off to him.  Claire Short on the other hand, with her constant U-turns and eventual capitulation of stance on resignation, has utterly disgusted me with her opportunistic shift in position- I hope she gets everything she deserves politically.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Is the UK/US really going to give 2 fingers to the international community and substitute violence for laws and agreement?<br>
What next? If China decides that Taiwan is a threat, are they entitled to blow it to smithereens? If the UK decides that Ireland is harbouring terrorists can they order the Irish prime minister to leave the country or face extinction?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
A brilliant point Bollix, and succintly made (wish I could learn to do that <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ).  Where the United States and Britain lead, others will see that they might well follow, backed up by the legitimacy of a precedent set by the world's two most powerful nations.  This has incalculable and disastrous consequences for peace and security all around the world.  While I find it highly unlikely that Blair will order the Taoiseach to leave Eire or face mlitary action(though it'd make London Irish's trip to Munster highly interesting <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )- I think the Taiwan example is a brilliantly spotted potential flashpoint created by a US-led pre-emptive doctrine.  A nation acting in a civilized way, mindful of its role and place in the world- cannot in all good conscience mount a pre-emptive war of aggression when a clear and proven threat has not even been established.  Outside of suspicion and personal beliefs Altaris- can you or anyone else anywhere on this thread or indeed anywhere in the world prove the veracity of a real threat?  Or how containment and deterrence have failed?  <br>
<br>
Prove to me that Iraq is a clear and imminent threat to US or UK security Altaris, and I undertake to support any military action that either of our governments take to correct this.  I pledge this unreservedly and have done so from the beginning- without a high standard of proof, pre-emptive acts of aggression can never be justified or yield wholly desirable results.  <br>
<br>
To conclude- my greatest fear in the long run has to be the far-reaching ramifications of any war, particularly for the Middle East.  Iraq is a wholly disunited nation in terms of ethnic, religious, cultural and territorial differences that exist within its borders.  I find it highly unlikely that any new government would be able to keep peace and security in a post-war Iraq.  Moreover, I feel very strongly that a semblance of a &quot;show-government&quot; Loya Jirga &amp; Afghanistan style will be the final result of any conflict.<br>
<br>
Altaris and Kadandrum- we will win the war, I have no doubt of that.  Your forces and ours are the finest in the world, and they face a de-fanged, flogged and demoralized army on the whole.  We will certainly win the war- but in the aftermath, how the devil will we win the peace with the instability of the region and the rise of extremist acts that will surely follow?  That is what will keep me up at night just as much as the thought of innocent blood being spilled daily in my name.<br>
<br>
