g positive force in the world. However, lately that very ideal has been turned upside down, to in effect say that since US is the good guy, everything it does must be good, right? And everyone to oppose or even disagree must be a bad guy, because only bad guys would do something like that.<br>
<br>
After the cold war and collapse of the Evil Empire, there weren't any obvious bad guys around, just slightly naughty ones. The problem with good and evil approach is that for good guys to exist, there has to be bad guys. Otherwise, there would be just... guys. The ones which are just as dead were they hit by a smart bomb while huddling in their shacks next to a power plant or shot dead defending freedom, the right way of life and apple pie. We all know who emerged as the bad guys of the 21st century, so I won't go into that. I just want to point out that I believe that one reason in the US demonising its opponents is partly because of the belief that anyone who opposes them must be somehow morally inferior, and partly because of the need to create or augment bad guys to underline their own goodness.<br>
<br>
This is what has happened to France. The position of France hasn't been fundamentally different from multitude of other countries, only more vocal and admittedly, somewhat more arrogant. Somehow it ended up as a figurehead of the anti-war movement and so it became the target. The awe-inspiring propaganda machine that is the US media kicked into action. From cartoons to talk shows, from news reports to government statements the Americans were programmed what to believe and what to think about France. Where just a couple of months ago had been indifference, was now strong opinion; built from resentment, founded on ignorance. <br>
<br>
Even the smartest person has to form his/her opinion based on the available facts. Therefore, should the facts be skewed, so would be the following assumptions. A real life example of this simple fact is that a person who by all accounts is quite sensible, believes in earnest that &quot;They are in it for money, we are in it for safety.&quot; Substitute safety for power, or control if you will, and I'll buy that. <br>
<br>
Remember that while the US isn't dependant on Middle-East oil, it is very much dependant on imported oil. The oil market is one where demand is more or less the same, while supply can change by the whim of a sheik. Who controls the supply, controls the oil price. Who controls the Middle-East, controls the oil market. If you think removing an anti-American leader sitting on the world's second largest oil resource is just a coincidence, you're in for a surprise. Does anyone even entertain the notion that the US would allow for an unfriendly leader on the throne of Iraq? Especially after it has gone great lengths to show everyone what happens from that stance. While oil might not be all of the pie, it certainly is a large piece of it.<br>
<br>
Someone mentioned they don't want France on their team. I'm afraid it's not who you want anymore, it's who you can get. 'Your team' was made public recently, and in many of those countries public opinion is against this war even if the government isn't (eg. Britain, Japan, Australia etc). Politicians are usually quick on the uptake. If the same style of 'diplomacy' continues, the next governments in those countries won't be in your team anymore. Time will tell if this war is just an isolated incident, or (believe it or not, what I don't want to see) if it will mark a decisive shift for the worse in the world opinion of the US.<br>
<br>
Amicalement,<br>
<br>
-Xor<br>
