<br>
firstly, black and white:<br>
The US seems to be waging this war on moral absolutes, of good guys and evil guys. there is reassurance in this view that you are 100% correct. The view is widespread (axis of evil, war on terror, good guys v bad guys etc). It provides a balm to conscience if you have faith, truth, god, righteousness and justice on your side. It means you are right and can do no wrong.  However, i think it is far to simplistic a view. I am anti war in iraq at this time. That doesn't mean i love saddam hussein. I know that he is 'a bad man'. But for me, the world is alot greyer and not as stark as some would see it. I know that UK/US were happy at one stage to support him and not another, that lots of others have WMD, that war kills lots of people, that there is questionable international legitimacy for this war, that economic motives underly it, that security fears compound it, that sectarian/anti muslim feelings are part of it.<br>
I don't feel it is a simple and easy moral choice of good versus evil. And i am concerned, as should everyone, about people who are convinced they are absolutely and unshakeably right. Fundamentalism and zealotry combined with  military might are a dangerous combination wether wielded by Middle Eastern Dictators, muslim extremists or American leaders.<br>
<br>
second, if you haven't suffered / fought, don't comment.<br>
I think relg said that, unless you know what its like to be in the military and put your own life on the line fighting for freedom, then you should quiet down and stop criticising those running the risks to keep you safe. I could come from the other perspective, and say that i have seen the other side of the gun, and been part of the civilian population suffering under military occupation. my family have been locked up by the 'lawful authority' exercised by british soldiers wielding guns, a country where civilians have been murdered in cold blood by the army. <br>
However, i don't think that i, or anyone needs to have 'experienced' it before commenting on it. I haven't been subjected to racism, but i still know its a bad thing. I disagreed with apartheid even though i had never been to south africa.<br>
my point is, it should be the strenght of your argument which carries the day, what you say, not who you are. Obviously serving soldiers will bring an extra perspective though to these sorts of debates. nonetheless, everyone has a valid perspective.<br>
<br>
third, who do you call for when you are in need<br>
People generally call on the UN, not the US.  The UN is involved in peacekeeping and humanitarian operations all around the world. When did we vote for a US world police force? the legitimacy for international operations comes from the UN which is a body representative of the entire world, not just one country.<br>
<br>
fourth, who's next?<br>
afghanistan has already been invaded, iraq is in the process. who is next? iran and north korea have been mentioned, as has cuba. will the american juggernaut of war keep on rolling? why not france too? after all, if they are not 'with us' they are 'against us'.  Once america crossed the rubicon of starting a war without the UN, where will it stop? <p>Bollix Braker <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Warlord <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Officer <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Celestial Empire <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--> <br>
